05987nam a22007815i 9780812298499DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780812298499  a(DE-B1597)590730  a(OCoLC)1305846829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD1525b.Q65 2022 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a331.5/440973223/eng/202112271 aQuintana, Maria L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContracting Freedom :bRace, Empire, and U.S. Guestworker Programs /cMaria L. Quintana. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2022  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b11 b/w  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION Freedom Struggles and the Labor Contract -- tCHAPTER 1 Free or Slave?: A Genealogy of Labor Contract Coercion and Freedom -- tCHAPTER 2 Good Neighbors?: Contract Labor and the Limits of Freedom During the New Deal -- tCHAPTER 3 Japanese Braceros: The Co-Constitution of the Bracero Program and Japanese American Incarceration -- tCHAPTER 4 From Civil Rights to Immigration Restriction: The Search for U.S. Labor Rights in the 1950s -- tCHAPTER 5 Boricua Braceros: The New Deal and the U.S.-Puerto Rican Farm Labor Program -- tCHAPTER 6 Empire and Nation: Caribbean Independence and the Labor Programs in the British West Indies -- tEPILOGUE Civil Rights for Whom?: U.S. Civil Rights and the Labor Importation Programs -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY OF PRIMARY SOURCES -- tINDEX -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContracting Freedom is the first relational study of the origins of twentieth-century U.S. guestworker programs from Mexico and the Caribbean. It investigates these government-sponsored programs as the unexplored consequence of enslaved labor, Japanese American incarceration, the New Deal, the long civil rights movement, and Caribbean decolonization.In the World War II era, U.S. lawmakers and activists alike celebrated guestworker agreements with Mexico and the Caribbean as hallmarks of anti-imperialism and worker freedom. A New Deal-based conception of racial liberalism inspired many of these government officials and labor advocates to demand a turn toward state-sponsored labor contracts across the hemisphere to protect migrant workers' welfare and treatment in the postwar world. Their view of liberalism emphasized the value of formal labor contracts, bilateral agreements between nation-states, state power, and equal rights, all of which they described as advances beyond older labor arrangements forged under colonialism and slavery. Eighty years later, their conceptions of guestworker programs continue to shape political understandings of the immigration debate, as these programs are often considered a solution to offset the deportation regime, and as a response to increasingly rigid racist measures to close U.S. borders to migrants.Maria Quintana's compelling history shifts the focus on guestworker programs to the arena of political conflict, revealing how fierce debates over the bracero program and Caribbean contract labor programs extended and legitimated U.S. racial and imperial domination into the present era. It also unearths contract workers' emerging visions of social justice that challenged this reproduction of race and empire, giving freedom new meanings that must be contemplated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAgricultural laborers, ForeignzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aContract laborzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aForeign workerszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 0aRace re